result.execSummary:
The defendant Nat-Shawn M Johnson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver THC (<=200g), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(h)1.
  • Manufacture/Deliver THC (<=200g), a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(h)1.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation or extended supervision is revoked or will discharge with outstanding financial obligations due, a civil judgment shall be entered for the balance due.

Defendant shall maintain absolute sobriety.

Defendant shall not possess or consume any alcohol or controlled substance without a valid prescription and then take medication as prescribed.  

Defendant shall not associate with known drug users or be present where drugs are illegally purchased, packaged, sold, consumed, used or stored.

Defendnat shall not operate a motor vehicle without a valid license or proof of insurance and registration.  

Defendant shall not possess, buy, sell, trade, borrow or manufacture any weapons.

Defendant shall participate in all counseling and/or treatment programs directed by the probation agent and comply with treatment recommendations, including but not limited to a psychological evaluation and comply with recommendations.   

Defendant shall provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis.  Defendant has the right to request expungement of DNA analysis in writing through the Department of Justice.

Defendant shall submit to random drug screens and urine testing.  

Defendant shall notify the probation agent within 48 hours of being prescribed medication or any change in medication.  

Defendant shall provide proof of incoming and outgoing monies.

Defendant shall designate one pharmacy for filling all prescriptions.
Defendant shall obtain and maintain full time employment and stable residence.
Defendant shall undergo an AODA assessment and comply with treatment recommendations.

timeConds.notes: With Huber privileges consistent with the rules of the jail while the inmate maintains a minimum security status. The defendant, at the discretion of the Sheriff, may perform community service work as an inmate worker in the county jail and shall earn statutory good time for same.
